description.plain:
Britney Jean Spears (born December 2, 1981) is an American singer and actress. Born in McComb, Mississippi, and raised in Kentwood, Louisiana, she performed acting roles in stage productions and television shows (such as The Mickey Mouse Club) as a child before signing with Jive Records in 1997. Spears’s first and second studio albums, …Baby One More Time  and Oops!… I Did It Again, became international successes, with the former becoming the best-selling album by a teenage solo artist. Title tracks “…Baby One More Time” and “Oops!… I Did It Again” broke international sales records, with the former reaching number one in nearly every country it charted in. In 2001, Spears released her self-titled third studio album, Britney, and played the starring role in the film Crossroads (2002). She assumed creative control of her fourth studio album, In the Zone, which yielded the worldwide success of the single “Toxic.”

In 2007, Spears’s much-publicized personal issues sent her career into hiatus. Her fifth studio album, Blackout, was released later that year, and spawned hits such as “Gimme More” and “Piece of Me”. Her erratic behavior and hospitalizations continued through the following year, at which point she was placed under a conservatorship in February 2008, which was terminated on November 12, 2021 after almost 14 years. Spears’s sixth studio album, Circus, included global chart-topping lead single “Womanizer”. Its supporting tour “The Circus Starring Britney Spears” was one of the highest-grossing global concert tours in 2009. Later that October, “3”, from The Singles Collection became Spears’s third single to reach number one on the Billboard Hot 100. Her seventh studio album, Femme Fatale, became her first to yield three top-ten singles in the United States: “Hold It Against Me”, “Till the World Ends” and “I Wanna Go”. She also served as a judge during the second season of the American version of The X Factor. After leaving her label of many years and joining RCA Records, Spears’s eponymous eighth studio album Britney Jean was released in 2013; it spawned the top 15 hit “Work Bitch”; however, it became the lowest-selling record of her career. Later that year, Spears began her debut residency Britney: Piece of Me at The AXIS at Planet Hollywood Resort & Casino in Las Vegas. In 2015 and 2017, the four-year show won the Best of Las Vegas award and became one of the most successful residencies of the area. It was later adapted as two international arena concert tours.

Spears was established as a pop icon and credited with influencing the revival of teen pop during the late 1990s. She became the ‘best-selling teenaged artist of all time’ and garnered honorific titles including the “Princess of Pop”. Her work has earned her numerous awards and accolades, including a Grammy Award, six MTV Video Music Awards including the Lifetime Achievement Award, nine Billboard Music Awards, and a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. In 2009, Billboard ranked her as the 8th overall Artist of the Decade, and also recognized her as the best-selling female artist of the first decade of the 21st century, as well as the fifth overall. The Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) named Spears as the eighth top-selling female artist in the United States, with 34 million certified albums. Nielsen SoundScan ranked her the tenth best-selling digital artist of the country, with more than 28.6 million digital singles as of January 2012. She has sold over 100 million albums worldwide and over 100 million singles, making her one of the best-selling music artists of all time. Rolling Stone recognized her instant success as one of the Top 25 Teen Idol Breakout Moments of all time and “…Baby One More Time” as the greatest debut single of all time, while VH1 ranked her eleventh on their “100 Greatest Women in Music” list in 2012, and Billboard named her the sexiest woman in music. Forbes reported that Spears was the highest paid female musician of 2012, with earnings of $58 million, having last topped the list in 2002.

description.plain:
Toxic is a dance-pop/techno-pop song with elements of bhangra music, “Toxic” features varied instrumentation, such as drums, synthesizers, and surf guitar. It is accompanied by high-pitched Bollywood strings, sampled from Lata Mangeshkar and S. P. Balasubrahmanyam’s “Tere Mere Beech Mein” (1981), and breathy vocals. Its lyrics draw an extended metaphor of a lover as a dangerous yet addictive drug.

Here is the deconstruction of the production of the music :

description.plain:
“Oops!… I Did It Again” is a song recorded by Britney Spears for her second studio album, Oops!… I Did It Again (2000).

It was nominated for the Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance during the 2001 ceremony. Commercially, the track peaked at number nine on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100.

Producer and writer Max Martin intended this to be his version of Barbra Streisand’s “Woman In Love.”

description.plain:
“Make Me…” is about lust and sex. RCA Records released the song on July 15, 2016, marking Britney’s first solo venture since 2013’s Britney Jean.

The song immediately climbed to No. 1 on the iTunes singles chart. Spears described the ranking on Twitter:

https://twitter.com/britneyspears/status/753827340120055812

The song features G-Eazy and is the first time the two have collaborated. He confirmed the collaboration in May 2016 in an interview with German magazine Bravo.

https://twitter.com/britneyspears/status/769597202842787840

The official music video for the song was released on August 5th.

description.plain:
“Womanizer” was released as the lead single and first track from Britney Spears‘ sixth studio album, Circus (2008).

It’s basically saying, ‘We know what you’re up to.’ It’s about guys cheating on girls. It’s a girl anthem. That’s why I like it.
—Britney Spears on Z100

It was well received by contemporary critics, with reviewers praising its hook, melody, and empowering lyrics. Critics also observed it was a stand-out track from its album and also deemed it as a comeback single for her.

The song was a commercial success, peaking at the top of the charts in Belgium, Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, Norway, Sweden, and the United States. It also reached the top ten in every country it charted in.

“Circus” is a song recorded by Britney Spears for her sixth studio album of the same name. It was released on 2nd December 2008 as the second single of the album.

In the track Britney compares her life to the chaos and grandiose of a traditional circus.

It was very well received by contemporary critics, with reviewers complimenting Spears' confident persona, while praising its electronic production.

“Circus” was a commercial success, peaking inside the top-ten in Australia, Canada, Denmark, New Zealand, and Sweden, while reaching top-twenty positions in many European countries.

The song was remixed for its music video release, with the second verse performed by Tinashe. The album version still features Britney Spears alone.

songs.full_title: Man On the Moon by Britney Spears
songs.title: Man On the Moon

description.plain:
“Man on the Moon” is the fourth track from Britney Spears' ninth studio album, Glory, released under RCA Records on 26 August, 2016.

The song utilizes space and astrological imagery to create a scene of Spears cosmically pining for a lost love. The use of the phrase “man on the moon” becomes an extended metaphor for someone far away. She misses him to such an extent that if feels as though he is a world away.

The track is laden with references to historical events and figures from the space race, such as the iconic phrase “Houston, we’ve had a problem”—said during an emergency on the Apollo 13 mission to the Moon in 1970—and Neil Armstrong, the first human to step foot on the surface of the Moon.
